      <sec id="s2c4">
        <title>Note 2</title>
        <p><italic>It is an elementary, although perhaps surprising, result (see </italic><xref rid="pone.0065245-Anderson1" ref-type="bibr">[<italic>15</italic>]</xref><italic> for example) that </italic><inline-formula><inline-graphic xlink:href="pone.0065245.e443.jpg"/></inline-formula><italic> is equal to </italic><inline-formula><inline-graphic xlink:href="pone.0065245.e444.jpg"/></inline-formula><italic>: that is, in a normal regression setting, when testing for association between </italic><inline-formula><inline-graphic xlink:href="pone.0065245.e445.jpg"/></inline-formula><italic> and</italic><inline-formula><inline-graphic xlink:href="pone.0065245.e446.jpg"/></inline-formula><italic>using a likelihood ratio statistic, it does not matter which way around one does the regression. Thus the above results also link the Bayes Factor with the test statistics from the “reverse” regressions, </italic><inline-formula><inline-graphic xlink:href="pone.0065245.e447.jpg"/></inline-formula>.</p>
